  "prompt": "Donated blood is mixed with sodium citrate?",
  "response": "Yes, that's correct. When blood is collected for donation, it is typically mixed with sodium citrate, which serves as an anticoagulant. Here's why:\n\n1. Anticoagulant purpose: Sodium citrate prevents the blood from clotting during collection and storage by binding to calcium ions, which are necessary for blood clotting.\n\n2. Preservation: This allows the blood to remain liquid and prevents it from forming clots before it can be processed and used for transfusion.\n\n3. Standard practice: This is a standard procedure in blood banking and collection centers worldwide.\n\nThe typical ratio is usually about 1 part sodium citrate solution to 9 parts whole blood, though this can vary slightly depending on specific protocols.",
